{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2goncharova_ver03/data/sn83045462/00280605207/1948123101/0377.xml":{"full_text":"Many Expansion Plans\nCalled Off by Industry\nAfter Dewey's Defeat\nPresident's Message\nAwaited Before Action\nIs Taken on New Plants\nBy David Lawrence\nPresident Truman may be the man\nof the year and his election and\nthat of the Democratic Congress\nmay have been the surprise of the\nyear, but the biggest news story of\nthe year has not yet been published.\nIt involves the extent to which\nthe election of Mr. Truman caused\nsuch a psychological shock to the\neconomic system as to have reduced\nby many billions of dollars the\namount of money that will be spent\nin 1949 for new' plants and equip\nment and general expansion of phys\nical facilities.\nThis is something not talked about\nopenly but businessmen privately\nhave been worrying about it a great\ndeal more than the newspapers have\nhinted. Many an expansion program\nthat was all ready to go in the event\nof Gov. Dewey's election has now\nbeen suspended and in many in\nstances canceled.\nThis will show up during 1949\nin curtailed employment. Already\nthere is a rise of unemployment.\nThe figures show' that the planned\nexpenditures for the first quarter of\n1949 are down as compared with the\nsame quarter of 1948.\nTax Rate Feared Most.\nThe estimates which the Com\nmerce Department received from va\nrious industries concerning their\nplanned expenditures for the first\nquarter of 1949 were practically all\nprepared before the 15th of Novem\nber-most of them obviously before\nthe election. Many companies did\nnot change their plans immediately\nbut decided to wait and see whether\nPresident Truman and the Demo\ncratic Congress were going to be as\nradical as the campaign speeches\nindicated. When they saw that Philip\nMurray, president of the CIO, was\nto be the dominant figure in the\ncoming administration and that an\nexcess-profits tax and repeal of the\nTaft-Hartley Act were to be the\nprincipal demands to be pressed\nupon the new administration and\nCongress, businessmen began to feel\nalarmed.\nWhat is most feared was that\nthe new tax rates would force a\ndiscontinuance of the business ex\npansion program. This arises out\nof the direct attack by the radicals\non sums earned which have been\nused hitherto to finance plant ex\npansion. If corporation earnings\nare to be diminished so that less\nand less money is available for\neven the customary dividend rate\nof prewar years and if companies\nfind it necessary to borrow on bond\nIssues because, they cannot raise\ncapital in the equity markets, then\nthe whole economic system is due\nfor a slowdown.\nThe chief trouble with the excess\nprofits tax is that it assumes a\nlarger and larger demand for goods\nwhereas there are evidences now\nthat supply is catching up with de\nmand. At the very time when busi\nness needs to be encouraged, it is\nbeing discouraged.\nThere are many businesses which\nare going ahead as usual but it does\nnot take a very large proportion of\nthe total to bring about a downward\nturn.\nThe two biggest factors in the\nmaintenance of good business con\nditions are, first, an ability to\nfinance largely out of earnings\nwhatever new plant may be required,\nand. second, some stability in the\nlabor-management situation.\nWait Truman Message.\nWith the economic power of la\nbor unions about to be increased\nmaterially, so that there is no\nlonger a balanced relationship be\ntween management and labor, the\nitem of indeterminate wage costs\nlooms so large as to make planning\nalmost impossible in large-scale\nbusiness.\nFor several weeks now business\nhas been awaiting the President's\nmessage and has been listening to\nreassuring gossip that Mr. Truman\nand the Democrats ate really con\nservatives at heart and would not doi\nanything to hurt the economic sys\ntem. Nobody, of course, ever be\nlieved that Mr. Truman or the\nDemocrats would deliberately kill\nthe goose that lays the golden egg\nof Government revenues at a time\nwhen the budget appears to be\nheaded for another deficit. But, on\nthe other hand, both the President\nand the Democratic leadership have\nvery little practical knowledge of\nwhat causes business to turn down\nward and very little understanding\nof what makes the wheels of in\ndustry go round. Unwittingly both\nMr. Truman and the Democrats can\nbring on a depression and can also\nblame business for bringing it on.\nCertainly, the administration will\nnot sit idly by while business re\ncedes without blaming somebody for\nIt, and the last people in the world\nto be blamed will be the legislators\nwho will have tampered with the\neconomic system at a very critical\ntime.\nThe President\u2019s message will point\nthe way.\nIt will either confirm the fears\nof businessmen or it will so greatly\nreassure them as to improve the\nbusiness outlook for 1949. Certain\nly there is a big log-jam of orders\nfor plant expansion and replace\nment of equipment which will be\naffected favorably or unfavorably\nby what Congress does on taxes and\nlabor legislation.\n(Reproduction Rishts Reserved.)\nCar Oil Change Held Needed\nOnly Once in 4,000 Miles\n\u2022y th\u00ab Associated Press\nThe Government's chief buying\nagency said yesterday it is unneces\nsary to change the oil in a car more\noften than once every 4.000 miles.\nTire Bureau of Central Supply\naa:d that was \"generally speaking.\u201d\nIt noted exceptions in cases where\n\"operating conditions include stop\nar.d-go service especially in cold\nweather or when sand and dust are\nregularly encountered.\u201d\nThe bureau estimated that the\nGovernment can save $500,000 a year\nby making oil changes in its vast\nfleet of cars, trucks and buses \"only\nin the spring and fall, or every 4.000\nmiles, whichever comes first.\u201d\n\"Under normal driving conditions\nand controlled preventive mainte\nnance. oil changes at periods of less\nthan 4.000 miles are unnecessary,\"\nthe bureau said.\n\u201cOil is wasted by changing too\nfreouently.\u201d\nThe bureau said its conclusions\nwere reached in studies made by a\ntechnical committee on lubricants\nand liquid fuels. Major oil and\nlubricant consuming agencies were\nrepresented on the committee.\nThis Changing World\nU. S. Task Fleet Prepared to Remove\n2,500 Marines From Tsingtao\nBy Contantine Brown\nPreparations are being made by\nVice Admiral Oscar Badger, com\nmander of the American task fleet\nstationed at Tsingtao, to remove the\n2,5 00 Marines\nj and other Amer\nicans in that\nChinese seaport\neither to Japan\nor the United\nStates when the\nCommunist\narmies reach the\ncity.\nAs soon as the\nAmerican naval\nand land forces\nhave left, T-ung\ntao it is expected\nto be taken over\nby the Russian\nNavy and con\nConstantine Brown.\nverted into a submarine base. The\nport was developed first by the\nGermans after the Kaiser forced\nthe Chinese to grant Germany a\nterritorial concession after the\nBoxer rebellion.\nThe prospects are not pleasing,\neither to Washington strategists or\nto Gen. MacArthur, but there is\nlittle that can be done about it. We\nare in that Chinese port at the in\nvitation of Generalissimo Chiang\nKai-shek with the avowed purpose\nof protecting our own and other\nWestern nationals against bandit\nactivities.\nRed Armies Closing in.\nThe Communist armies which are\nclosing in on Tsingtao have had un\nofficial communication with Amer\nican authorities, and have informed\nus that while they will treat Amer\nican naval forces as honored guests,\nthe Reds\u2019 strict organization and\ndemonstrated ability to prevent\nhooliganism will make our stay in\nTsingtao as a police force unneces\nsary.\nAdmiral Badger has no choice.\nHe may remain for a short while\nafter ,the city is occupied by Mao\nTse-tung's forces, but eventually he\nwill have to move away with his\nentire fleet. Our top military and\nnaval strategists are fully aware\nthat, as soon as we have withdrawn,\nthe Communists will prepare to in\nstall a fleet of Soviet ocean-going\nsubmarines at that base, thus com\npleting the arc which the Soviets\nhave built around Japan since V-J\nday.\nTsingtao is considered more im\nportant to the Soviet high command\nthan either Vladivostok or Port Ar\nthur. It is a warm water port, a\nshort distance from the southern\nmost Japanese island of Kyushu and\nis closer to Formosa and the Philip\npines than the other two Soviet\nnaval bases.\nThe establishment of a Soviet sub\nmarine base at Tsingtao is not\nfeared because of its possible strik\ning power in wartime. Soviet sub\nmarines are engaged in ferrying\nmilitary equipment and agents to\nstir up disturbances in Formosa anc'\nthe Philippines.\nReports from Formosa.\nDuring the last six months Amer\nican intelligence services have had\nreports from both Formosa and the\nPhilippines of the mysterious ap\npearance of Russian-manufactured\nmilitary equipment, as well as of the\narrival of well-known Communist\nagitators. These are believed to have\nbeen landed in secluded spots which\ncannot easily be guarded.\nThe arrival of war equipment and\nsubversive agents has been particu\nlarly frequent recently in Formosa,\nwhich may become Generalissimo\nChiang Kai-shek's new headquar\nters after he is compelled to evac\nuate Nanking.\nChinese administration of For\nmosa has been neither wise nor\ncautious. Chinese sent to govern the\nisland after the Japanese surrender\ntreated the Formosans as badly as\nthey did the Japanese. There has\nbeen a move in recent months, en\ncouraged apparently by a former\nChinese Ambassador in Washington,\nfor a Formosan plebiscite on making\nthe island an American trusteeship.\nBut this belated move has not\ngained many adherents.\nMao Tse-tung\u2019s agents have been\nhard at work taking advantage of\nthe demoralization which exists in\nthe island and the natives\u2019 bitter\nness against the Chinese adminis\ntration. They have gained much\nground. The fact that we failed to\nsave Gen. Chiang from disaster,\nwhile the Chinese Communists won\nspectacular victories with Moscow\u2019s\nhelp, also has impressed the Formo\nsans, who, like all orientals, believe\nin physical power as demonstrated\nin military successes.\nThe establishment of a Red naval\nbase at Tsingtao is expected to ad\nvance Soviet plans in the Pacific\nand will enable Russian submarines,\ncarrying arms and agents, to make\nmore frequent trips to the South\nPacific and the Indian Ocean.\nWhite House 'Sport\u2019\nTruman Holds Upper Hand With Press;\nConferences Will Take Fire in Few Weeks\nBy Doris Fleeson\nAs a result of his surprise victory,\nPresident Truman is enjoying with\nthe press if not quite a honeymoon,\nat least a temporary lease on the\nupper hand. In\na tepid seven\nminute confer\nence this week\nno serious effort\nwas made to\noutflank him or\nto develop the\nmany controver\nsial aspects of\nhis problems.\nThe President\nis clearly sa\nvoring the situa\ntion as evi\ndenced by his\nclean hit in the\nby-play on hif\nDoris Flerson.\nscheduled meeting with congression\nal leaders. The President mentioned\nthat Senator Lucas would attend\nthe meeting; when a reporter sug\ngested that the Senator had not\nbeen elected majority leader the\nPresident riposted that the report\ner\u2019s guess on that might be better\nthan his election predictions.\nThe reporters, still blushingly con\nscious of their poor showing as po\nlitical prophets, roared and the\npresidential staff which always hov\ners anxiously over him at press con\nferences, beamed proudly on their\nboy.\nKind of Sporting Event.\nMr Truman\u2019s press conferences\nhave always been a unique kind of\nsporting event in which the game\nstalked by reporters was the un\nwary Truman comment that showed\nwhere the body was buried. Not\nsince his early White House tenure\nhas the President been a ready\nfountain of news; he got burned so\noften during that talkative phase,\nhe was persuaded to shift the bur\nden to the press. Now his usual\nopener is that he has no news, are\nthere any questions. Occasionally\nhe reads a prepared statement or\nmakes a formal announcement.\nUnlike Franklin Roosevelt, the\nPresident never uses his press con\nference for exposition of his pro\ngram or for some pyrotechnical dis\nplay that will steal the headlines\nfrom a rival politician, perhaps from\nmaters reflecting on his administra\ntion. Mr. Truman is neither that\narticulate nor that artful: his ad\nmirers would probably put it that\nhe is too honest for such maneu\nvers though they are certainly le-;\ngitimate politics and valuable weap\nons.\nIn fact there does not now exist j\nin the White House any apparatus\nfor the full use of the White House\nsounding board to further the Tru- 1\nman program. A few aides are use\nful to reporters they know and\ntrust; politicoes who deal with the\nPresident are co-bperative. But\nnews is never developed at the\nWhite House; they wait for it to\nhappen.\nOften Gives in Big Way.\nThe President remains the repor\ntorial ace tn the hole. He obviously\nstarts out. as at public meetings,\nmeaning to be discreet. But if a\ntopic can be located on which he\ncurrently has a gripe or an in-1\ndividual hit upon who has annoyed\nhim\u2014and he has a low boiling point\non personalities\u2014he gives, often in\na big way.\nThe Truman administration is\nvery press-conscious. The White\nHouse official wit, Maj. Gen.\nVaughan, who seems to have out\nlasted George Allen in that depart-'\nrnent. has nicknames for individual\ncolumnists, most of them highly\nunflattering, it is perhaps unneces\nsary to add. Great capital is made\nin the inner circle of mistakes made\nby these individuals who venture:\nbeyond the obvious.\nThe holiday interval, of course, is\nthe time of great preparations and\nof decisions not yet quite final.\nThree important messages to Con\ngress next month: it is easy and\nhonest for the President to reply!\nthat questions asked will be dealt\nwith in those messages. But when\nthe Democrats get rolling on.their\nmany campaign promises, the White\nHouse press conference will take fire.\nPilot's Skill Saves 15\nIn B-29 Crash Landing\nBy tH\u00ab Associated Press\nFAIRBANKS. Alaska, Dec. 31\u2014\nA pilot\u2019s coolness and skill were\ncredited yesterday with saving 15\nmen from possible disaster in ar,\nemergency B-29 landing at Ladd\nField.\nThe big bomber's fuselage broke\napart when the plane veered into a\nsnowbank Wednesday night. The\naccident occurred after a propeller\nspun away from an outboard en\ngine just after the plane had be\ncome airborne for a flight to its\nhome base at Rome, N. Y.\nThirteen 'of the men aboard es\ncaped injury. Two were hospi\ntalized. A civilian passenger broke\nhis foot in jumping to the ground\nand a member of the plane crew\nsuffered severe frost bite in the 35\noelow-zero cold.\nThe pilot, Lt. William F. Falconio\nof Gary, W. Va., circled the field on\nthree engines at low altitude, but\nran into trouble when the nose\nwheel collapsed halfway down the\nrunway on the landing It swerved\ninto a snowbank and cracked the\nfuselage just ahead of the wing.\nThe plane is assigned to the Air\nMateriel Command at Griffiss Air\nForse Base, Rome, N. Y.\n4 Children Die in Fire\nOn Louisiana River Front\nMONROE. La., Dec. 31.\u2014Four\nchildren were burned to death when\nfire from a kerosene heater ex\nplosion destroyed their riverfront\nhome yesterday.\nTheir parents. Mr. and Mrs. Wil\nlie Kelly, narrowly escaped the\nflames with another child. Patsy, 9\nmonths old. The mother and father\nsuffered burns in attempts to res\ncue the other children.\nKilled were Lillian. 15: Clara Ed\nda, 6; Victor, 4, and Joseph Lloyd, 2.\nJaps Get Right to Fly\nRising Sun Flag Again\nBy th# Associated Prats\nTOKYO, Dec. 31.\u2014Gen. Mac\nArthur gave the Japanese back their\nflag today, telling them they could\nfly it any where, any time.\nThus, for the first time since the\nsurrender, the rising sun emblem;\ncan flutter from the staffs of Japan;\nwithout special permission.\nGen. MacArthur in a special New;\nYear's message also mentioned \"na\ntionalism \"\u2014a word almost taboo now\nin this land where fanatic national\nism led to war and misery.\nGen MacArthur said he hoped the\nflag would stand as \u201ca firm advocate\nfor a concept of nationalism ever\nsubordinate to the universal laws\nwithin the family of nations.\u201d1\nHe also hoped it would \u201cserve as\na shining beacon to summon every\nJapanese citizen resolutely to the\nduty of building Japan's economic\nstature to insure and preserve Ja\npan's political freedom.\u201d\nThe supreme commander praised\nthe Japanese for their progress to\nward recovery since the end of the\nwar. He urged them to choose wise\nly in the general elections January\n23 so as to preserve their new-won\nfreedom.\nMODERN FLOORS\nMubin.\nRontals\u2014Salas\u2014Ropairs\nAD. 7575:2431 18th St. N.W.\nRESORTS. NEW YORK\nPENN POST HOTEL\n3*4 Weft 31ft Street, N. T. C.\nOPPOSITE PENN STATION. Cleaa.\ncomfortable reeaw. (MifuUt rataa.\nLOUIE\n\u2014By Harry Hanan\nrr\u00ab- S5S 3\nOn the Record\nFrench Seen Winners on Ruhr Measure;\nReaction in Germany Is Dismaying\nBy Dorothy Thompson\nThe new year begins with an\nevent of incalculable end results,\nbut predictable repercussions.\nThe French government has won\nregarding t n e\nRuhr. This great\nGerman indus\ntrial basin will\nbe taken out of\nGerman hands\nand placed \"per\nmanently\" un\nder control of an\nintemat tonal\ncommittee con\nsisting of repre\nsentatives of the\nFrench, Belgian,\nDutch, Luxem\nbourg, British\nand United\nStates govern\nDorothy Thompson.\nments. me occupying puwcis wm\nact for Germany, which has three\nvotes out of 15, with eight to con\nstitute a decision. This authority\nwill control distribution of Ruhr\ncoal and steel, the justification of\nthis policy being to prevent Ruhr\nproduction from again being used\nas a means of German rearmament.\nDespite restricting clauses, es\npecially paragraph 26. the commit\ntee\u2014composed of Germany's indus\ntrial competitors\u2014Is almost bound\nto exploit German resources in be\nhalf of their own nationals, this be\ning the way of men when given ac\ncess to spoils.\nGame of Greed and Grab.\nThere will be little unity of in\nterest, but each will seek to outvote\nthe others in his own behalf. The\nproduct of a great complex of in\ndustries will become the focus of\npolitical logrolling. In this game of\ngreed and grab, the United States\u2014\nwith its interest in restoring a viable\nGermany economy In place of the\nirrational chaos now costing the\nAmerican people billions a year\nwill be caught in a position where\neach vote will cost us some friend.\nThe repercussion in Germany is\nalready dismaying. It threatens the\nprobability of any Western German\ngovernment being established, for it\nis doubtful whether a German gov\nernment dependent for authority\non the popular suffrage could co\noperate with this measure and sur\nvive. So we shall have intensifica\ntion of anarchy.\nAlready every party in Germany\nfrom Communists to Christian Dem\nocrats is united against it. But the\nCommunists who now\u2014as in 1918\n\u2014are the first to raise the banner\nof German nationalism, are out in\nfront with the charge that Germany\nis to become a colony of Western\nimperialism, and with cries of trea\nson against Germans who have col\nlaborated with the West.\nThe measure will give, in the first\nline, leadership to the working\nmasses. It is likely to have precisely\nthe same effect as the French occu\npation of the Ruhr in 1923\u2014and\neventually be answered with the\nsame weapon. In 1923 the German\nworkers in the Ruhr staged a gen\neral strike, with such effect as to\nbreaK the occupation 1aut also bring\non the disastrous inflation which,\nmore than anything else, paved the\nway for Hitler.\nCan Sabotage Measure.\nThe German workers can sabotage\nthis measure. Not a ton of coal\ncan be mined without them. And.\nin a strike, leadership will be taken\nby Communists, and workers of East\nand West will unite against the\nWestern powers.\nWalter Lippmann, just returned\nfrom Germany, has warned against\nthe possibility of civil war. That\npossibility has existed since 1945,\naw\u2019aiting the spark to set it off. The\nblind, egoistic tenacity of the French\nhas, I fear, furnished that spark.\nBut for the new resistance only\nthe Communists are prepared while,\nwith a single piece of paper, we may\nundermine all the work of the past\nthree years.\nTo have constructive results, the\nEuropeanizing of the Ruhr (to\ngether with the heavy industries of\nBelgium, France and Luxembourg) i\ndemands a federal union of West-1\nern Europe, including Germany.\nBut, yielding to the French, we have\nratified another booty-politic, bring\ning the unification of Germany un- i\nder Russian leadership closer.\nBefore 1949 is out we shall see\nthe effects of the Ruhr policy. Given\na miracle, and loyal application of\nall clauses, it may work out so as\nnot to worsen the existing situation.\nBut the outlook for 1949 is not bet\nter than it was for 1948.\n<Relea\u00bb\u00abd by The Bell Syndicate. Inc.) j\nArgo Party Brightens New Year\nFor Industrial School Youths\nHie thought of the New Year and\nthe promise of better things to come\nseemed to dominate a party which\nthe fortunate children staged for\nthe unfortunate ones.\nThat s the way it was last night\nin the Industrial Home School at\n2453 Wisconsin avenue N.W, as\nthe young people of B'nai B'rith\nWomen. Argo Chapter, played host\nto the children at the school.\nFor one month they had planned\nthe program of entertainment\nwhich brought many a cheer from\nthe school's members when they\nweren't busy with the noise-makers\nand other favors, or eating the ice\ncream and cake.\nByron Smith, 17, of 1404 Primrose\nroad N.W. was B\u2019nai B\u2019rith's master\nof ceremonies. Three 17-year-old\nvocalists of Argo furnished music.\nThey were Basha Newman. 1836\nSeventh street N.W.; Joyce Tres\nkonoff, 4711 Georgia avenue N.W.,\nand Bette May Keerman. 4461 South\nDakota avenue NJ5. Some more\nmelodies were supplied by Lee Levy.\n14, of 3557 Sixteenth street N.W., a\nB'nai B\u2019rith youngster who played\nthe accordion.\nThe idea of making all the chil\ndren in the school happy through\nthe party brought an Interesting\nsentiment from Pauline Weiner. 23,\nof 734 Hamilton street N.W.. a young\nwoman of B\u2019Nai B'rith who did a\nlot towards making the event a\nsuccess.\n\u2022\u2019We're pretty fortunate on the\noutside and these children haven't\ntoo much.\u201d she said. \"We got a big\nkick out of bringing them joy.\u201d\nHow the 31 young people from\nB'Nai B'rith reacted to the sugges\ntion that they give the party was\nexplained by Phyllis Blumberg, 15,\nof 4316 New Hampshire avenue N.W.\n\"As soon as we heard about the\nidea, we all wanted to do it,\u201d she\ncommented.\nMrs. Frank Fields, chairman of\nArgo Chapter\u2019s juvenile delinquency\nprogram, suggested that other organ\nizations undertake to stage parties\nfor children, because, she contended,\nnot enough is being done along these\nlines.\nShe joined with Mrs. Julius Kirson\nof Argo, chairman of B\u2019Nai B'rith's\nyouth activities in the Metropolitan\nArea, and Mrs. Nathan Simkowitz,\npresident of Argo, in directing\u2019 the\narrangements.\nArgo presented a ping-pong table\nto the school to top off the function.\nReport of Flare Turns Hunt\nFor Lost Plane to Bahamas\n\u2022y the Associated Press\nMIAMI, Fla., Dec. 31.\u2014Aircraft\nsearching for a missing DC-3 char\nter airliner with 32 persons aboard\nconcentrated on the Bahamas today\nafter flares were reported seen in the\nvicinity of Andros Island.\nYesterday a vessel near the Ba\nhamas group reported sighting a\nflare. Seven Air Force planes were\ndiverted to the area in the hope\nthat some trace of the airliner\u2014\nmissing since Tuesday morning\u2014\nwould be found, but no evidence of\nwreckage or survivors was sighted.\nThe Coast Guard said, however,\nthat the entire group would be\nscanned again today.\nAn unconfirmed report that sur\nvivors had been seen on the coast\nof Cuba was ruled out yesterday\nafter aircraft flew low over hun\ndreds of miles of rugged Cuban\ncoastline.\nThe plane was last heard from\nearly Tuesday. A faint radio mes\nsage from the plant reported its\nposition at about 50 miles south of\nMiami.\nIt was returning to Miami from\nSan Juan, Puerto Rico, with 29 na\ntive Puerto Ricans\u2014including two\nbabies\u2014and a crew of three aboard.\nWishing You a\n\u201cHAPPY NEW YEAR\u201d\nLEWS\n3644 14th St N.W... CO. 1184\nOPEN EVES. TIL 9 P.M.\nFrt* Parking 1447 Irring St. N.W.\nChurch Mortgage Paid Off\nBy Anonymous Donor\nBy th\u00ab Associated Press\nREADING, Pa., Dec. 31.\u2014The\nmortgage on the Bethany Lutheran\nChurch in West Reading is all paid\noff but church officials don't know\nwhere the money came from.\nAn anonymous Good Samaritan\nwho last April contributed $5,000 to\nward the reduction of the mortgage\nfinished the job yesterday. He paid\noff the $6,500 still due.\nThe Rev. Paul J. Kidd, pastor,\nsaid he had received the mortgage\npapers marked \"paid in full\u201d from\nan attorney who said he was swom\nto secrecy about the identity of the\ndonor.\nTEACHERS\nImmediate Positions\n$220 to $380 Month\nAdams Teachers Agency\nC\u00ab1\u00abr\u00bbd* Bid*.. 11th ft G N.W. BE. 3938\nEDUCATIONAL.\naJcouWtamcy\nPace Courses in Ac\ncountancy and Finan\ncial Administration\nleading to B. C. S. and\nM. C. S. Degrees.\nC. P. A. Preparation.\nCo-educotionol Day\nand Evening Classes now forming.\nSend for 42nd Yeer Seek\nBENJAMIN FRANKLIN UNIVERSITY\n1100 16tk St., N. W. et L RE 2262\nMcLemore\u2014\nCalls on 'Pen-Pals'\nTo Have Patience\nBy Henry McLemore\nEver bite off more thap you can\nchew?\nI have.\nJust did, in fact, about six weeks\nago.\nmat was wnen i\nI wrote that the\nchildren of Ja\npan want pen\npals on this side\nof the Pacific\nand that if the\nboys and girls\nover here were\ninterested I\nwould handle\nthe details.\nSeems as if\nhalf the chil\ndren in the\nUnited States\nwant to ex\nMcLemore.\nchange letters witn Japanese cnn\ndren. American boys and girls have\ncome close to wearing out my post- j\nman, Mr. Scott. He didn't mind the\nextra loads of letters at first, be\ncause he is a stamp collector and\nthe stamps we pulled off together\nwere ones he wanted. But he has\na sufficiency now, and hinted that\nthe pen-pal letters be sent to the\nNew York office of my syndicate.\n\u201cThey must have more postmen\nin New York than they do in Day\ntona Beach,\u201d he said.\nSmothered by Letters.\nThat was a good idea, not only\nfor Mr. Scott but for me. When\nI wrote the pen-pal column, I didn't\nhave any idea that the response\nwould be so great. I figured that\nI could easily handle the two or!\nthree dozen letters which I ex\npected to get. But when the letters\ncame by the hundreds, and then by\nthe thousands, I began to get j\nalarmed. Beihg smothered by let\nters, even if they show some one\nis reading my column, is not my\nidea of the perfect death.\nSo. In the future, will all you\nyoungsters who want to correspond:\nwith Japanese youngsters of your\nown age or thereabouts, please\nsend the letters to the McNaught\nSyndicate, 60 East Forty-second\nstreet, New York 17. New York, and\nbe sure to write \u201cPen-Pal'' on the\noutside of the envelope. They will\nbe handled by Miss Priscilla Brad-1\nley and forwarded to Mrs. M. P.j\nEchols in Tokyo, who will see that;\nthe letters are distributed in the\nJapanese schools.\nOh. yes. before I forget. Don\u2019t\nyou children be so impatient about\nhearing from Japanese children.\nOne little girl in North Dakota has\nwritten me three very indignant\nletters asking why she hasn't heard\nfrom a little girl in Tokyo. Kyoto,\nOsaka or Yokohama. You must\nremember this: While all of the\nletters you write are bundled up\nand air-mailed to Tokyo, you won't\nbe getting airmail letters back. It\ncosts 25 cents and up to send a\nletter from Japan to America, and\nright now the Japanese children\ndon\u2019t have that sort of money to\nspend. They must send their replies\nby boat, and that takes quite a\nwhile.\nPaper Precious, Too.\nToo, you must remember that\nwhile it is easy for you to write\na letter in English, it is awfully\ndifficult for the Japanese children.\nYou try to write a letter in Japa\nnese. and you'll have some sort ofj\nan idea of how much work it is for\nchildren over there to compose a\nletter in your language. My guess\nis that the average Japanese school\nchild will spend at least a week on\nthe letter before he thinks it worthy\nof being sent to a friend in America.\nPaper is very precious, too. They\nhave to save their pennies for the\npaper, and even when they have\nsaved enough, there isn't always j\npaper to be bought. And most of\nthe Japanese children decorate their\nletters with pen and pencil and\nwater color sketches of themselves,\ntheir homes or the cities in which!\nthey live.\nSo, please be patient. Every letter\nthat has come to me is on its wav:\nto Japan, and some day the answers\nwill start pouring in.\nDistributed by McNeueht Syndicate, Inc.) j\nDIAMONDS\nBARGAINS IN SOLITAIRES\nWEDDING RINGS, ETC.\nALWAYS AVAILABLE\nARTHUR MARKEL\n940 f ST. N.W. NA. 0284\nFloors Sandra. Cleaned. Pollened\nInstalled. Repaired\nWaxes. Finishes. Supplies Bold\nIBIS rath Street N.W\nSea utile 1070\nW> ALL MAKES\nATER\nHEATERS\nGE. 1068\nSAMUEL C. BOYD, INC.\nWATCH REPAIRING\nClock gt\u00bbn All Work\nBopoirint jyc Gaorootock\nWatch Crystals. Mo\nU/AhC'C WATCHES\nYY Al/C J DIAMONDS\n1*09 E St. N.W. JEWELRY\nStart the New Year Right\nDo the right thing\nlor your home\nprotect it with good\n1 paint Paint inside\nand outside, bright\nen up the floors;\ncheer up the walls,\nbut use only qual\nity brand pa